<section class="full-height" id="intro">
<div class="bcg" id="climate-change">
  <div class="fill-lite" style="width: 80%; margin-left:10%;text-align:center">
    <div class="hsContainer">
      <div class="hsContent" style=" color: black; background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); font-size: 1em;">
        <p>Climatic suitability was modeled using 1) occurrence data, 2) digital maps of climate, and 3) a statistical model to associate these two types of information.</p>
        <p>Occurence data are records of a species occurring at a particular location, i.e., the latitude and longitude where the species was found. We used occurrence data from the Botanical Information and Ecology Network(<a href="http://bien.nceas,ucsb.edu/bien">BIEN</a>). Much of the data in BIEN are derived from natural history collections (herbarium specimens), but they also include the locations of U.S. Forests Service forest inventory plots(<a href="http://www.fia.fs.fed.us">Forest Inventory and Analysis, FIA</a>), and other published sources of data (see <a href="http://bien.nceas.ucsb.edu/bien">BIEN</a>). The number of occurrences used per species ranged from 1,324(<i>Juniperus scopulorum</i>) to 14,626(<i>Pseudotsuga menziesii</i>) among our nine focal species. These sample size reflect the number of data points after eliminating duplicate points falling within the same 1kmx1km grid cell.</p>
        <p>Two types of digital maps of climate were used - current climate and future climate. Current climate data were used to construct a model of a species' climatic niche and predict its current geographic distribution; future climate data were used to predict the species' geographic distribution under future climates resulting from alternative greenhouse gas emission scenarios - <em>Representative Concentration Pathways</em>(RCP's). We projected future distributions under two such scenarios, RCP 2.6 and 8.5.</p>
        
        <p>For both current and future climate data, we used digital maps from the most recent(fifth) assessment report from the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change(IPPC AR5), statistically-downscaled and bias-corrected by the U.S. National Aeronautics and Space Administration (<a href="https://portal.nccs.nasa.gov/portal_home/published/NEX.html">NASA</a>) to a resolution of 30 arc-seconds(~1km<super>2</super>
        ). For all years (1950-2095), we first averaged across a single replicate from each of four <em>General Circulation Models</em>(<em>GCM</em>)  to obtain monthly precipitation, maximum temperature and minimum temperature data. The four GCMs were CSIRO-Mk3.6.0, HADGEM2-ES, MIROC5, and MPI-ESM-LR; this selection of GCMs was informed by a recent comparison
        <super>1</super> 
        of the performance 17 GCMs at matching historical patterns of the North American climate(e.g., cool season Western Atlantic cyclones, the North American monsoon, the U.S. Great Plains low-level jet, and Arctic sea ice). These data represent model simulations that are  hindcasts for the period 1950-2006, and forecasts for the period 2006-2095.</p>
        <p>We used these GCM-averaged temperature and precipitation data to calculate 19 bioclimatic variables(described <a href="http://www.worldclim.org/bioclim">here</a>) for the period 1960-2095. These bioclimatic variables capture aspects of climate expected to be important for the survival, growth, and reproduction of many organisms - mean annual temperature, mean annual precipitation, precipitation in the hottest three months of the year, mean temperature in the coldest three months of the year, etc.</p>
