<section class="full-height" id="method-detail">
<div class="bcg">
  <div class="fill-lite" style="width: 80%; margin-left:10%;text-align:center">
    <div class="hsContainer" >
      <div class="hsContent" style=" color: black; background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); font-size: 1em;">
        <p>We then calculated "current climatic normals" by averaging each of the 19 bioclimatic variables across the years 1950-2000. Future climate normals were calculated by averaging across 30-year windows centered on each of the decades from 2020 to 2080 (2006-2035, 2016-2045, 2026-2055, 2036-2065, 2046-2075, 2056-2085, 2066-2095).</p>
        <p>Statistical modeling of climatic niches and geographical distributions was conducted using the freely-available algorithm <a href="http://www.cs.princeton.edu/~schapire/maxent/">Maxent<super>2</super></a>. Maxent employs a maximum entropy method to model a species' climatic niche; it has performed well in comparisons among competing methods<super>3</super>
          . Maxent compares the climate where the species is known to occur against a sample of the "background"-here, all of the contiguous western United States within the Northern Latitudes 24.06&#176; and 49.94&#176; and the Western Longitudes -125.02&#175; and -97.18&#176;. Model parameters that best distinguish the climate where the species is known to occur from the background climate constitute the "climatic niche model". We used all 19 bioclim variables as predictors in Maxent, with the default settings for features and regularization. The model output (Maxent "raw" probabilities) is a prediction of the relative suitability of each grid cell in the landscape - relatively better vs. worse for a given species, in terms of climatic conditions. That is, Maxent predicts the relative occurence rate of a species
          <super>4</super>. This model of the climatic niche was then used to project (forecast) the species' distribution into the future, using the future climate normals described above.</p>
        <p>We converted predicted current and future relative occurrence rates to an absolute scale by calibrating them against expert maps of each species' distributions
          <super>5</super>
          . We did this in two ways. First, for each species, we divided the Maxent raw output scale into four categories that captured cumulatively 5%, 36.7%, 68.3%, and 100% of the cells where the species is present, according to the expert range map. This generated a map with four categories, which can be thought of as "not present" vs. low, medium, and high probability of presence. These are maps shown in the google-earth interface. A second-set of maps were produced that dichotomized the Maxent raw output scale into "not present" vs. "present", using the critierion of the lowest overall error rate(including both false positives and false negatives), compared to the expert range maps. These maps were the basis for our analyses of change in area that is "climatically-suitable" per species, per rcp, per forest type, and per habitat type. "Hurricane tracks" were calculated from the centroid of the prediced species range through time.</p>
